    Metadata 
Contributors 
Miroslav Sirota, 
Marie Juanchich, 
Kelly Wolfe, 
Andrew H. Tyner, 
Zachary Loomas, 
Olivia Miske, 
Bri Luis [SCORE] 
Description 
This study aims to replicate the main claim reported in Yang et al.’s (2013) experiment 1. The 
authors reported that the more prospect’s frame was associated with risk, the less buyers were 
willing to pay for that prospect: Framing a risky prospect as a “lottery ticket” (i.e., increased risk 
and uncertainty) reduced participants’ willingness to pay for the prospect, compared with to an 
uncertain “gift certificate” (i.e. reduced risk and uncertainty). This claim was tested using an 
online between-subjects experiment (Amazon Mechanical Turk participants). Participants 
indicated their willingness to pay for a risky prospect that was framed as either a “lottery ticket” 
or an “uncertain gift card”. In the lottery condition, the “lottery ticket” would for sure yield either 
a $10 or a $20 Best Buy gift card (both equally likely). In the gift card condition, the “gift card” 
would be either a $10 or a $20 Best Buy gift card (both equally likely). To clarify, the two 
conditions had the same chance (50/50) and amounts to win, only the framing of the prospect 
was different. Participants were told that the authors would randomly select five respondents 
to get a $20 bonus and an opportunity to purchase a lottery ticket or a gift card with this bonus. 
If their willingness to pay was above the reservation price (the reservation price of $15 was not 
revealed to participants), they would buy the lottery ticket or gift card at the authors’ 
reservation price. If their willingness to pay was below the reservation price, they would not buy 
the lottery ticket or gift card. 
 
 
The authors analyzed and compared willingness to pay with a t-test (Yang et al., 2013, p.726): 
“Participants in the lottery condition were willing to pay less (M = $5.68, SD = $6.69, Mdn = 
$5.00) than participants in the gift card condition (M = $9.52, SD = $4.48, Mdn = $ 7.50; t(99) = 
3.43, p < .001, p 2 = .11; z = 2.93, p = .003).” The present study will replicate this claim, which has 
been selected for the SCORE program. 
