Study Information 
Hypotheses 
H* (SCORE focal test): Participants in the lottery condition will have a lower mean willingness to 
pay than participants in the gift card condition.  
  
In line with the results of the original study, participants who have been selected for the lottery 
condition are likely to want to pay less for the prospect framed as a lottery ticket compared to 
participants in the uncertain gift card condition. Their willingness to pay is characterized as the 
minimum amount in US dollars provided by participants. No additional hypotheses are 
included in this experiment. 
Design Plan 
Study type 
Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or 
lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized 
controlled trials. 
Blinding 
For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they 
have been assigned. 
Is there any additional blinding in this study? 
Participants will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned. In practice, 
this means that participants are not aware of the inclusion of the second condition and are not 
aware of both conditions having the same design (i.e. both prospects have the same value and 

chance). Additionally, the researchers will not manipulate or oversee to which conditions 
participants are assigned to. Which conditions participants are assigned to will be clear to 
researchers once the data has been collected in full 
Study design 
The experimental design is between-subjects with 1 factor (condition) with two levels (lottery 
ticket or uncertain gift card). This design is true to the design of the original study and has not 
been altered. 
No files selected 
Randomization 
Participants will be randomly assigned to either the “lottery ticket” or “gift card” condition via 
Qualtrics’ (the online survey platform that was used by authors) Survey Flow Randomizer, which 
randomly assigns each participant to one of the conditions while ensuring that the conditions 
are evenly presented/assigned over time (i.e. checked “Evenly Present Elements” box). 
Participants are randomly assigned to one of the two conditions at the start of the study, when 
the Qualtrics survey is accessed. For more information on Qualtrics randomization, see 
https://www.qualtrics.com/support/survey-platform/survey-module/survey-flow/survey-flowove
rview/  
 
Sampling Plan 
Existing Data 
